# OOP Principles

## Core Pillars

- **Encapsulation** — Hide representation (`Data` subtypes), expose behavior (`map`, `evaluate`, `toNode`). No public mutable fields.
- **Abstraction** — Program to interfaces (`Mapping`, `JSONataResult`, `BuiltInSupplier`), not concrete evaluators.
- **Polymorphism** — Dispatch via interface methods and sealed/type hierarchies, not `instanceof` chains.
- **Composition** — Build complex mappings by combining simpler ones (`MappingJoin`, `CompoundFunction`), not deep inheritance trees.

## Tell, Don't Ask

Objects own their behavior. Callers **tell** what to do; they do not **ask** for state and decide externally.

```java
// ❌ Ask — caller inspects type and branches
if (data instanceof ArrayData array) {
    for (var item : array.items()) { /* ... */ }
} else {
    /* ... */
}

// ✅ Tell — behavior stays on the object
data.map(mapping, context);
```

- Push decisions into the type that holds the data (`Data.map`, `JSONataResult.toNode`).
- Avoid getters followed by external `if/switch` — add an intent-revealing method instead.
- Law of Demeter follows naturally: no `a.getB().getC().doD()` chains across layers.

## Design Guidelines

- Keep inheritance depth ≤ 2; favor `record` + interface for simple value carriers.
- Replace switch-on-type with polymorphism only when behavior is stable and cross-cutting.
- Co-locate behavior with data it operates on (methods on `Data`, not external static helpers).
- Factory methods (`jsonata(...)`, `Data.load(...)`) hide construction complexity.

## Red Flags

- God classes accumulating unrelated JSONata features.
- Static mutable state shared across evaluations.
- Subclasses overriding methods to disable parent behavior.
- Leaking internal collections that callers can mutate.
- Callers that query object state and implement domain logic outside the object.
